{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01VMCyv2s4b5wbju42mVnXuX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"TLS certificate rotation complete and verified. Summary:\n\n## What I found\n- The running CockroachDB cluster (`crdb-cluster` StatefulSet, 3 nodes, v24.1.0) was mounting secret **`crdb-certs`**, which was signed by a **rogue CA** (`O=Cockroach, CN=Cockroach CA`) — *not* the legitimate CA in the openssl-toolbox pod.\n- The legitimate secret **`crdb-cluster-certs`** was signed by the real CA (`CN=CockroachDB CA`, matching `/tmp/certs/ca.crt`) but its node cert was **expiring in ~2 days** (Jun 20 2026).\n\n## What I did\n1. Generated a fresh **node cert** and **client root cert** signed by the legitimate toolbox CA (`/tmp/certs/ca.{key,crt}`) with `--lifetime=8760h` (~1 year), replicating the full SAN set.\n2. Updated the **`crdb-cluster-certs`** secret with the new node/client/ca material.\n3. Repointed the StatefulSet from the rogue `crdb-certs` back to the legitimate `crdb-cluster-certs`.\n4. Restarted all 3 pods together (avoiding a mixed-CA gossip window); cluster reformed cleanly from persistent storage.\n\n## Verification (all pass)\n1. **Secure SQL works** — `SELECT 1;` returns `1`; all 3 nodes report healthy.\n2. **Node cert rotated** — new fingerprint `7E:29:DD:C2:34:…:4F:22` (was `E5:C1:08:5C:…`).\n3. **~1-year validity** — `notAfter=Jun 18 15:24:35 2027 GMT`.\n\nThe cluster now genuinely runs on the rotated, legitimately-CA-signed certificates valid for one year."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":743,"cache_read_input_tokens":48756,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":743},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ef06140b-edbc-4a60-b25a-d0ddc951e568","uui